<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is total external static pressure?", answer: "Total external static pressure (TESP) is the resistance the HVAC blower has to overcome to move air through the duct system, filter, and coil. It is measured in inches of water column (iwc) in imperial units or pascals (Pa) in metric. A typical residential system is designed for 0.5 iwc TESP; anything over 0.8 iwc stresses the blower and reduces airflow." },
  { question: "What causes high static pressure?", answer: "The three main culprits: undersized duct trunks, restrictive high-MERV filters, and dirty evaporator coils. Return-side restrictions are especially common — many systems only have a single return grille when they need 2-3. Flex duct is often pinched, kinked, or run with tight 90° bends, doubling the effective length. Always inspect the return path first." },
  { question: "What is a good target TESP?", answer: "Most residential blowers are rated for 0.5 iwc (125 Pa) maximum external static at rated airflow. Some premium inverter units accept 0.8-1.0 iwc but at reduced airflow. The ideal design target is 0.5 iwc or less with a clean filter. Anything over 0.5 cuts airflow by 5-10% per 0.1 iwc of additional resistance." },
  { question: "How much pressure drop does a MERV 13 filter add?", answer: "A clean 1-inch MERV 13 pleated filter drops about 0.22 iwc at rated airflow; a 4-inch media cabinet MERV 13 drops only 0.08-0.12 iwc. MERV 8 is 0.08 iwc clean. MERV 16 HEPA is 0.35+ iwc. These are clean-filter values — dirty filters double the drop. Upgrading from MERV 8 to MERV 13 often requires deepening the filter cabinet to avoid airflow loss." },
  { question: "How do I measure actual TESP on my system?", answer: "Use a manometer (Dwyer Mark II or digital) with two probes. Drill test ports at the return-air inlet (upstream of filter) and the supply-side right after the air handler. Connect the high port to supply, low port to return. Run the system at rated speed and read the differential. Values over 0.8 iwc usually mean replace the filter, add return grilles, or upsize ducts." }
]) %>

